    pearls: ["The reflex grading scale is 0-4+: 0 absent, 1+ diminished, 2+ normal, 3+ brisk without clonus, 4+ sustained clonus -- always document the numeric grade and compare bilaterally","A positive Babinski sign is ALWAYS pathological in adults and indicates corticospinal tract dysfunction -- it is normal only in infants under 12 months whose corticospinal tracts are not yet fully myelinated","The Jendrassik maneuver (patient hooks fingers together and pulls apart during testing) augments reflexes by distracting the patient and reducing cortical inhibition -- always use before documenting areflexia","Hyperreflexia with Babinski sign localizes the lesion ABOVE the reflex arc (UMN), while hyporeflexia localizes it AT or BELOW the arc (LMN) -- this distinction is critical for differential diagnosis","Clonus is tested by rapidly dorsiflexing the ankle; sustained clonus (≥3 beats) is always abnormal and indicates significant UMN dysfunction; unsustained clonus (1-2 beats) may be normal in anxious patients","An inverted reflex (absent at one level with hyperactive response one level below) is pathognomonic for cervical myelopathy and warrants urgent MRI"],
